32 SECTION 2. Section 7A of chapter 128 of the General Laws, as so appearing, is hereby
33 amended by inserting after the definition of “'Healthy soils practices” the following definition:-
34 “Regenerative agriculture”, agriculture that improves the health of soils, including but not
35 limited to consideration of depth of topsoil horizons, water infiltration rate, organic carbon
2 of 5

36 content, bulk density, biological activity, biological diversity and bare ground, and as achieved
37 through practices such as conservation tillage or no-till, cover-cropping, planned grazing,
38 integrated crop-livestock systems, synthetic chemicals reduction and other methodologies, and is
39 conducted in consultation with the commission for conservation of soil, water and related
40 resources established in section 19 of chapter 21.
41 SECTION 3. Said chapter 128 is hereby further amended by inserting after section 7F the
42 following section:-
43 Section 7G. (a) The department shall develop a program to compensate farmers for
44 ecosystem services, including carbon sequestration, water filtration and biodiversity protection.
45 The program shall link payments to measurable outcomes, verified by third-party assessments.
46 (b) The department shall prioritize funding for: (i) controlled-climate agriculture,
47 including the construction and retrofitting of greenhouses and controlled-environment agriculture
48 systems; (ii) projects utilizing renewable energy or sustainable materials; and (iii) farmland
49 preservation and access, including establishing a revolving loan fund offering zero-interest loans
50 for farmland purchases, prioritizing historically underserved farmers.
51 (c) The department shall prioritize urban agriculture development by: (i) supporting the
52 transformation of vacant urban lots into community farms or gardens through targeted grants;
53 and (ii) expanding its urban agriculture program with funding for soil testing, season-extension
54 infrastructure and educational programs.
55 (d) The department shall prioritize renewable energy and sustainability by: (i) developing
56 agrivoltaics projects to provide incentives for solar energy projects on agricultural lands that
57 maintain or enhance crop production; (ii) establishing funding for research on the impact of solar
3 of 5

58 installations on agricultural productivity; (iii) offering discounts under the farm energy discount
59 program of not less than 25 per cent; and (iv) expanding grants for energy efficiency
60 improvements and electrification of farm equipment.
61 (e) The department shall support agricultural education by: (i) fully funding vocational
62 agricultural programs and on-farm internships, prioritizing BIPOC and underserved
63 communities; (ii) providing student debt relief for graduates working in agriculture-related fields
64 for at least 10 years; (iii) building technical assistance networks by establishing a coordinated
65 network of agricultural advisors to provide long-term support for farmers; and (iv) funding
66 UMass Extension to serve as a central hub for technical services and climate resilience
67 education.
68 (f) The department shall reform its grant program by: (i) simplifying the application
69 processes, including through the development of a centralized online portal for state agricultural
70 grants; (ii) allowing self-labor and used equipment purchases as eligible grant expenses; and (iii)
71 improving the equity and accessibility of grants, including though: (A) offering bridge loans for
72 farmers requiring upfront payments for grant-funded projects; and (B) ensuring translation
73 services for grant applications and outreach materials.
74 (g) The department shall conduct biennial agricultural surveys to collect data on land use,
75 production and economic impact. The department shall use data collected through these surveys
76 to assess the effectiveness of state programs and adjust investments accordingly.
77 (h) There shall be within the department a state agriculture resilience task force to
78 oversee the implementation of this section. The task force shall coordinate with UMass
79 Extension and other relevant agencies as necessary to implement this section.
